100 years young! 6 women honored during centenarian ball at retirement community

by JESSICA A. BOTELHO | The National Desk

Thu, February 1st 2024 at 5:22 PM
Updated Fri, February 2nd 2024 at 9:54 AM
23
VIEW ALL PHOTOS
Isobel Sherman (right) recently turned 100. She smiles with Benjamin Saccocia, the assistant director of life enrichment at Halcyon West Bay in Rhode Island on Wednesday, Jan. 31, 2024. (Photo: Jessica A. Botelho/The National Desk)

WARWICK, R.I. (TND) — Six women were honored at a retirement community’s first-ever centenarian ball.

Residents and staff at Halcyon West Bay in Rhode Island gathered to celebrate the milestone birthdays.

For Rosalee Malaby, who turned 103 in December, the secret to longevity is making sure she keeps a healthy routine and good habits. She also thinks she's been fortunate in life.

I've gotten dropped off the Lord's list," Malaby said with a smile during an interview with The National Desk.

Malaby said she never imagined she’d live so long, but she certainly is grateful. She said she loves going for walks and reading books, such as mysteries and historical fiction.

But her own personal history is far from fiction, as she served a registered nurse in the U.S. Army during World War II.

Two days after her 21st birthday, she received a letter from the government that noted, “We have not drafted nurses yet.”

I figured their emphasis was on 'yet,'" she said, adding that she decided to enlist soon after. "I was between training and a job, so I figured I decided I'd go and volunteer and that's what I did."

Malaby served in the war for 15 months. She was stationed in the Philippines and Japan.

"I went over with a group of people -- doctors and nurses -- that were going to staff 3,000-bed hospitals that were going to take casualties from the invasion of Japan," she said. "Well, when they dropped the bomb, they didn't have to invade, so they sent us onto Japan to the Army of Occupation."

There, she treated American soldiers, as well as the nation's allies. She said the experience was frightening at times, but something she doesn’t regret.

It wasn't like anything I'd ever done before,” she said. “It was kind of -- do what you're told because you don't know what was happening. Seeing airplanes shot of the air and knowing there were human beings in there bothered me.”

Still, she said, she had to get used to it because she knew she had an important task to perform: saving lives.

"That's what nursing is," she said.

She also acknowledged that the war impacted everyone, whether they were serving the country or not.

"There was nobody that was over 5 years old and less than 100 that wasn't involved in this war," she said. "I don’t care if you were [home] or in the service. Food was rationed, women were leaving their children with their mothers or mother in laws and going to work because they had to have labor, and the men were all gone. Everybody was involved.”

When she returned to the United States, she was ready to start the rest of her life. She got a job at Denver Children's Hospital in Colorado and went on to begin a family.

Eventually, she made her way to Rhode Island. She has been living at the retirement home since 2011.

I know that I'm taken care of," she said.

Malaby, along with her loved ones, attended a celebration in her honor at the retirement home Wednesday afternoon. They were joined by Malaby's fellow centenarians, including Dorothy Ferrelli, Isobel Sherman, and Rita Gendron.

Gloria DiFolco, who is 100, and Ruth Lundin, who is 101, couldn’t attend, but received citations from the State of Rhode Island.

During the event, Sherman, who recently turned 100, danced with Benjamin Saccocia, the assistant director of life enrichment at Halcyon.

I do my best to show the other seniors that you can still continue with your life," she said, adding that she enjoys participating in a variety of activates at Halcyon, such as chair volleyball and chair yoga. "I keep going."

Gendron celebrated her 101st birthday in November. She was surrounded by family during the event and said the secret to a long, happy life is obeying your parents.

She recalled the first and only time she didn't tell her mother and father where she was going one day. Her father tracked her down and took her home.

"I got lectured all the way there, until I went to bed -- and the next day -- that I was never to do that again," she said, noting that she learned her lesson.

Gendron said she always enjoyed cooking, knitting, and sewing. In fact, she made a career out of sewing, as she worked at NATCO making airline bags.

She’s been at Halcyon for five years now.

Everything was great," she said of the celebration. "They did a fantastic job."

Ferrell agreed. A few of her family members flew in from Florida to be by her side at the event, including her granddaughter, Deb.

"It's a big deal to get to 100," Deb said. "Then, every year after that, it's a lot to celebrate. She’s outlived the entire family as far as her siblings and my grandfather's siblings. My grandfather's siblings all lived to 100, as well. There are good genes on both sides, which is a good thing."

Ferrelli, who turned 103 in December, has been at Halcyon for six years. She loves trivia gatherings and when the retirement home hosts live entertainment.

Bombshell Betty performed on Wednesday, singing and dancing for the birthday girls, as well as the rest of the residents.

The best part of the day was halfway through the program when we all started relaxing, eating, and enjoying it,” Ferrelli said.

Bombshell Betty said she performs in a lot of nursing homes and assisted living facilities. She specializes in senior entertainment and was thrilled to take part in the big day.

"The fact that six different women at the same place are celebrating being centenarians within the same event is amazing to me," she said. "I remember when getting to 100 was something that was rare. But now, we're living better, we're living healthier, we're living longer -- and these ladies are as sharp as tacks.”

Steven Lowinger, who is the owner of Halcyon West Bay, donned a sparkly tie during the festivities. He greeted residents as they sipped wine and snacked on appetizers and dessert with their loved ones.

"This is why I do what I do ... celebrating over a century of life 6 times ... what could be better?" Lowinger said.

Melissa Stock is the executive director. She shared similar sentiments.

"I've worked in the senior care industry for over 18 years and celebrations like today are the icing on the cake," Stock said. "We spend so much time with our residents we become an extended family over time. These 6 amazing women have lived over 100 years; just think how amazing that is. The experiences and stories they have to share are so inspiring. I am so humbled to be able to share in this celebration for them. We look forward to making this an annual event here at Halcyon West Bay. Our residents deserve nothing less."
